import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.List;

public class Solution {
    private void dfs(int node, int parent, int bob, int time, int[] aliceIncome, int[] res, int[] amount, Map<Integer, List<Integer>> tree) {
        if (time < bob || amount[node] >= 0) {
            aliceIncome[0] += amount[node];
        } else {
            aliceIncome[0] += amount[node] / 2;
        }
        amount[node] = 0;
        boolean isLeaf = true;
        for (int child : tree.get(node)) {
            if (child != parent) {
                isLeaf = false;
                int[] tempIncome = {aliceIncome[0]};
                dfs(child, node, bob, time + 1, tempIncome, res, amount, tree);
            }
        }
        if (isLeaf) {
            res[0] = Math.max(res[0], aliceIncome[0]);
        }
    }

    public int maxNetIncome(int[][] edges, int bob, int[] amount) {
        Map<Integer, List<Integer>> tree = new HashMap<>();
        for (int[] edge : edges) {
            tree.putIfAbsent(edge[0], new ArrayList<>());
            tree.putIfAbsent(edge[1], new ArrayList<>());
            tree.get(edge[0]).add(edge[1]);
            tree.get(edge[1]).add(edge[0]);
        }
        int[] res = {-100000};
        int[] aliceIncome = {0};
        dfs(0, -1, bob, 0, aliceIncome, res, amount, tree);
        return res[0];
    }
}
```


    We will use a depth-first search (DFS) to calculate the net income for Alice as she travels towards the optimal leaf node. We create a tree using the given edges, and then call our DFS function starting at node 0.

In the DFS function, we distinguish between whether Alice has reached the node before Bob or not. If Alice has reached the node before Bob or if the gate at node i gives a reward (amount[i] >= 0), we add the price needed / cash reward to Alice's net income. If Alice and Bob reach the node simultaneously, we add half of the price needed / cash reward to Alice's net income. We set amount[node] to be 0 after calculating Alice's net income.

We then recursively call the DFS function for all child nodes (except the parent node), with the current node acting as the parent. If we reach a leaf node, we update the maximum net income for Alice.

Finally, we return the maximum net income for Alice.
